'We know well that the world looks with great attention at everything that happens at Pompeii,' Franceschini said as he stood before a fresco of Dionysius and Aphrodite in the villa's main salon. 

'Today, Italy is proud to say to the world that we have turned a page.'

Pompeii, a busy commercial city overlooking the Mediterranean, was destroyed in A.D. 79 by an eruption of Mount Vesuvius that killed thousands of people and buried the city in 20 feet of volcanic ash. 

